    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP) is the rule that every user, process, or service should only have the minimum access rights necessary to perform its job—no more, no less. In a real office network, this means you grant a marketing employee read/write access only to the sales database and the marketing intranet, while denying them access to the HR server or the finance ledger. It also means you create separate service accounts for the file server, giving them just enough permission to upload and download files, but not to alter system settings or run as Administrator.\n\nWhy does this matter? By limiting privileges, you reduce the attack surface and contain potential damage if an account gets compromised. It also makes auditing easier, since you can quickly see which accounts are actually using which resources. In a nutshell, PoLP keeps your network secure and organized by ensuring that every key is only used for the lock it was meant to open.\n\nLet me give a quick example: imagine your office network has three main segments—IT, Finance, and Marketing. Under PoLP, the IT segment would have full control over the file server and the network infrastructure, the Finance segment would only be able to read/write to the finance database and the finance",
