    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Principle of Least Privilege acts as a built-in guardrail against internal threats by ensuring that even a malicious insider can only reach the specific resources they need. If an employee starts acting weird—say, trying to touch files they shouldn't—their limited permissions will immediately block them from moving beyond their own department or from accessing sensitive data outside their scope. This containment is crucial because it means that any unauthorized activity is confined to a narrow area, making it easier to detect, investigate, and contain.\n\nFor example, consider a senior analyst in the finance department who suddenly starts trying to read the HR database. Under PoLP, their account would only have read/write access to the finance ledger and the HR shared folder, but not to the IT network or the marketing database. If they try to move laterally, the system will reject any attempt to access those restricted resources, alerting the admin through audit logs. This way, the insider threat is contained to the finance segment, and the rest of the network remains safe.\n\nIn practice, this also helps with accountability. Since each account is tied to a specific set of permissions, you can quickly identify who did what and when. If an internal threat occurs, you can trace the activity back to",
